e psychical and psychological characteristics that the authorities believed made a fighting man, and how evaluations changed as the war dragged on. He also brings to light the experiences of those who deliberately claimed disability to avoid service – a minority within the large population of rejected volunteers who felt denigrated, if not emasculated, by their exclusion from duty.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMilitary service, VoluntaryzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918zCanada. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War I.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311127402708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015z978311127703508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311142000440uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077482890140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774828901423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774828901/original  a978-3-11-127402-7  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-127703-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-142000-4  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles